To further understand the process of how the phosphate anions were adsorbed onto the adsorbents surface, the equilibrium data were fitted to Langmuir, Freundlich and Sips isotherm models (Fig. 7
                           , Table 3

                           ). The Langmuir model assumes that the adsorption occurs as a monolayer on a homogenous surface where the number of adsorptive sites is limited [48]. Freundlich model assumes that multilayer adsorption is possible, such that there is no saturation loading at high concentrations [49]. Sips isotherm model describes a combination of Langmuir and Freundlich isotherms derived to forecast adsorption in heterogeneous systems and bypass the limitation of increasing adsorbate concentration associated with the Freundlich isotherm [50]. At low adsorbate concentrations, it tends towards the Freundlich isotherm, whereas at high concentrations, it predicts monolayer adsorption in a way similar to the Langmuir isotherm [51].
